title: Leaves from the journal of our life in the Highlands, from 1848 to 1861 :
author: Victoria
snippet: We remained on deck till twenty-five minutesto nine, and saw many bonfires on the Scotchcoast — at Dunbar — Lord Haddington's place,Tyninghame, and at other points on the coast.

title: The heart of Midlothian;
author: Scott, Walter
snippet: " I was in the wood at Tyninghame when there was a sort of gallants hunting with my lord ; on my saul, there was a buck turned to bay made us all stand back — a stout old Trojan of the first head, ten-tined branches, and a brow as broad as e'er a bullock's.

title: The Prose Works of Sir Walter Scott. (Supplementary volume: containing notes, historical and illustrative, by the author, glossary, etc.)
author: Scott, Walter
snippet: " Brave !—brave enough, I warrant you," answered Norman; " I was in the wood at Tyninghame, when there was a sort of gallants huntingwith my lord; on my saul, there was a buck turnedto bay made us all stand back; a stout old Trojan ofthe first head, ten-tyned branches, and a brow asbroad as e'er a bullock's.
